<h1>Problem 871 - 2020 IMOSL, A3</h1>
<h2 class='difficulty'>Difficulty: 6</h2>
<p>Suppose that \(a, b, c, d\) are positive real numbers satisfying \((a+c)(b+d)=a c+b d\). Find the smallest possible value of
\[S=\frac{a}{b}+\frac{b}{c}+\frac{c}{d}+\frac{d}{a}.\]</p>
<h2>Thinking</h2>
<div class="skib">
<p>The inequality is homogenous so you can make \(abcd\) whatever, but that's besides the point.
\[S = \frac{ac(ad + bc) + bd(ab + cd)}{abcd}\]
</p>
<p>Also note \(ac + bd \ge ab + cd\) and \(ac + bd \ge ad + bc\) means that \(a\), \(c\) are either both bigger than or both smaller than \(b\), \(d\). WLOG \(ac \ge bd \).</p>
<p>Actually, we have a trivial minimum
\(S \ge 4\)
by AM-GM (of course not sharp).</p>
<p>I just realised that we <i>should</i> let \(abcd = 1\) for the sake of convenience because usually we would get \(ac + bd \ge 2\), now we get \(ac + bd = ab + bc + cd + da \ge 4\). This is monumental:
\[S = ac(ad + bc) + bd(ab + cd) \ge ac(2) + bd(2) = 2(ac + bd) \ge 8\]
And all this needs to be sharp is \(ab = bc = cd = da\), or \(a = c\), \(b = d\), which gives the equality case \(a = c = k(2 + \sqrt{3})\), \(b = d = k\), and we are done.</p>
</div>
<h2>Idea</h2>
<p>Don't be stupid. Use every condition. Also here's some intuition: \(ac + bd\) should be the `same size' as \(ab + cd\) and \(ad + bc\) - but it's the sum, so this gives you a simple bound on \(ac + bd\) which is twice the trivial bound you would have.</p>
